The SEM images were investigated for analyzing the morphology of the table tennis bat cypress baseplate powder (raw material). As it is illustrated in Fig. 1
                        (a–c), microtubule structures arranged from catheters of cypress wood (Fig. 1a and c), as well as abundant pits on the catheter walls (Fig. 1b) can be observed [21–23]. The EDS spectrum was also used for element analysis. From the extracted outcomes that are displayed in Fig. 1d, the table tennis bat cypress baseplate mainly contains the C, N and O elements with a high carbon content (Table 1
                        ), signifying the feasibility of preparing fluorescent carbon dots.
